Below is the updated email template with the additional **build.gradle repositories section** and **develop/main branch reference guidance** incorporated.

Dear Team,

Greetings from the DevOps / Platform Engineering Team.

As part of the GitLab Centralization Program, the migration of application repositories from the legacy GitLab instance (**gitlab.epay.sbi**) to the centralized SBI GitLab platform (**gitlab.sbi**) has been successfully completed.

To ensure uninterrupted development and deployment activities, all application teams are requested to review and comply with the governance standards and repository changes outlined below.

---

# 1. CI/CD TEMPLATE CONFIGURATION

All repositories must use the centrally managed CI/CD templates.

### Backend Services (Java/Spring Boot)

```yaml
include:
  - project: 'itepaypg-sbiepay2/infra/devops/cicd-templates'
    ref: main
    file: 'templates/ci/backend/java.yml'
```

### Frontend Services (React)

```yaml
include:
  - project: 'itepaypg-sbiepay2/infra/devops/cicd-templates'
    ref: main
    file: 'templates/ci/frontend/react.yml'
```

Please update the `.gitlab-ci.yml` file accordingly wherever applicable.

---

# 2. DOCKERFILE CHANGES (MANDATORY)

To standardize container builds, base images will now be injected dynamically during pipeline execution.

### Existing Dockerfile

```dockerfile
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
```

### Updated Dockerfile

```dockerfile
ARG BASE_IMAGE_DEV_ENV
FROM ${BASE_IMAGE_DEV_ENV}

# FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
```

### Action Required

* Comment out the existing `FROM` statement.
* Add the `ARG` and dynamic `FROM` statements shown above.
* Applicable to all backend and frontend repositories.

---

# 3. BACKEND REPOSITORIES – settings.gradle

For Java/Gradle-based applications:

* Remove or comment out the `settings.gradle` file from the repository.
* Build configurations are now managed centrally through shared CI/CD templates.
* Do not reintroduce this file unless specifically instructed by the Platform Engineering Team.

---

# 4. BACKEND REPOSITORIES – build.gradle REPOSITORY CONFIGURATION

For all Java/Gradle-based application repositories, any repository definitions configured within the `build.gradle` file must be commented out or removed.

### Example

**Before**

```gradle
repositories {
    mavenCentral()
    maven {
        url "https://some-repository-url"
    }
}
```

**After**

```gradle
/*
repositories {
    mavenCentral()
    maven {
        url "https://some-repository-url"
    }
}
*/
```

### Important

* Dependency resolution is now centrally managed through the CI/CD templates.
* JFrog Artifactory repositories are already configured within the centralized CI/CD framework.
* No repository configuration should be maintained at the application repository level.
* Introducing custom repository definitions may lead to build inconsistencies and governance violations.

---

# 5. BRANCH NAMING STANDARDS

Push rules have been enabled across all repositories.

Only the following branch naming conventions are permitted:

| Branch Type | Format                          | Example                          |
| ----------- | ------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Main        | main                            | main                             |
| Develop     | develop                         | develop                          |
| Release     | release/x.y.z                   | release/1.2.0                    |
| Feature     | feature/EPAY-<id>-<description> | feature/EPAY-123-add-upi-refund  |
| Bugfix      | bugfix/EPAY-<id>-<description>  | bugfix/EPAY-456-fix-null-pointer |
| Hotfix      | hotfix/x.y.z                    | hotfix/1.2.1                     |

### Important Notes

* Ticket number is mandatory for Feature and Bugfix branches.
* Description must be lowercase and hyphen-separated.
* Branches not matching the approved patterns will be automatically rejected.

---

# 6. COMMIT MESSAGE FORMAT

Commit messages must follow the format below:

```text
<TICKET>|<CC>|<TYPE>: <SUBJECT>
```

### Examples

```text
EPA-101|BE|feat: add UPI refund API endpoint
EPA-234|FE|fix: resolve payment form validation issue
EPA-305|IN|chore: update Dockerfile configuration
EPA-456|BE|refactor: optimize payment service logic
```

### Allowed Types

```text
feat
fix
docs
style
refactor
perf
test
chore
```

Commit messages that do not match the required format will be rejected by repository push rules.

---

# 7. PROTECTED BRANCH & MERGE REQUEST POLICY

Direct pushes to protected branches have been disabled.

| Branch    | Direct Push |
| --------- | ----------- |
| main      | Not Allowed |
| develop   | Not Allowed |
| release/* | Not Allowed |

All code changes must be submitted through Merge Requests (MRs).

### Approval Matrix

| Target Branch | Required Approval                                                        |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| develop       | Vendor App Lead                                                          |
| release/*     | Vendor App Lead + Vendor App Maintainer                                  |
| main          | Vendor App Maintainer + Vendor PM + Bank App Maintainer + Bank App Owner |

### Additional Requirements

* Successful pipeline execution is mandatory before an MR can be merged.
* Approval requirements cannot be bypassed.

---

# 8. ACCESS MANAGEMENT

Repository access is now governed exclusively through approved LDAP groups.

Please note:

* Manual project-level role assignments will not be provided.
* Access requests must be routed through the respective Project/Application Lead.
* Include the repository name and required LDAP group while raising the request.

